               . However, it is to be noted that it is the optimal face value of the bond that depends on
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $r_{t_{n}}$ \end{document}
               through
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $P^{*}_{t_{n}}=V_{t_{n}}( 1-\theta ) e^{-X^{*}-yT}/ \Lambda ( r_{t_{n}},\, 0;T) $ \end{document}
               . Thus, the bond face value depends on the initial interest rate level in a particular way such that, given the assumptions of the model,X* is independent of it. It is noted that, unlike in models with constant interest rates, the optimal coupon and face value at different restructuring points do not scale with the asset value because of their interest rate dependence.

Finally, unlike in the Leland (1998)‐type dynamic models with constant interest rates, the ratio of the couponCto the face valuePof each debt is different and depends on the interest rate level. Note that by the definition ofX

